American crony capitalism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the U.S. Treasury and its FMI allies shifted the blame for the problems in this region onto crony capitalism, lack of transparency, and inefficient governance?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the authority of their own entrepreneurs, East Asia has developed faster than any other region—and with greater stability—over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "You must be perfect to criticize others."
Enron used large accounting strategies and complex financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to gain influence and power, shape U.S. energy policy, and avoid regulations.
Patronage capitalism is not new, nor is it exclusive to a single party.
The former U.S. Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, would have tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the so-called independent accounting standards board attempted to clean up the accounting of the top executives' businesses.
It was partly because of him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was obstructed.
The enthusiasm of America to recapitalize airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free market is merely a thin veil for the benefit of old companies: giving to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and the problems were not revealed testifies to the absence of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it testifies to the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to focus on Enron, the number of members of Congress who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
Contributions to campaigns were not merely a matter of public interest, but constituted an investment.
Like most Enron investments, everything went smoothly in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some relate to politics: the Enron scandal strengthens the arguments in favor of campaign financing reform and the necessity of even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by business interests that in fact can buy elections.
The Bush administration refuses however to disclose information that would attest to the role of business interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons pertain to the economy, particularly the information economy.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals aimed at efficiently allocating resources to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
The control of accounts is intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guardians?
Who will control the account controllers?
We count greatly on motivations.
Audit firms desire to maintain their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory practices and accounting control practices leads to other perverse motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of controls could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the forgotten hero of the debacle.
But accounting firms and their corporate clients - which is nothing surprising, given the conspiracy that has developed - strongly attacked his proposal to separate advisory and accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood - and the Enron debacle so clearly showed - is that motivations are important, but that unregulated markets cannot themselves provide the best motivations.
The markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of schemes that Enron was implementing.
The new economy - and its new complex financial instruments - highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to confuse.
Instead of facing the problems, the American enterprise systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by the American system of favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time is to find the proper balance between government and the market.
The status quo will assert that Enron was an exception: that its disappearance was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must suffer the consequences and will suffer them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors state that its central practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act the same way.
They are right - and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received adequately reflects the economic situation of a company.
Under the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being offered these guarantees at the present time.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people around the world have no objections to the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we observe that they can manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes evident, new places of abuse are created over and over again - take the U.S. repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investment banking.
We have repeatedly seen the consequences of excesses from the unleashing of unregulated markets.
We must now resist the temptation to lean toward the other extreme.
The challenge is to achieve the right balance.
